cates for ways that workplaces, not women, must be changed. Addressing life stages ranging from graduate school through retirement, these essays represent a gamut of institutions and women who draw upon both personal experience and scholarly expertise. The contributors contemplate the slipperiness of the very categories we construct to explain the stages of life and ask key questions, such as what does it mean to be a graduate student at fifty? Or a full professor at thirty-five? The book explores the ways women in all stages of academia feel that they are always too young or too old, too attentive to work or too overly focused on family. By including the voices of those who leave, as well as those who stay, this collection signals the need to rebuild the house of academia so that women can have not only classrooms of their own but also lives of their own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aWomen in higher education - Social conditions. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aArner, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer-Maglin, Nan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBethman, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBickford, Donna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilis, Hélène E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Lynn Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoffel, Cynthia Miller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColatrella, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/